					<div class="row">
						<div class="twelve columns">
							<h4>Internet and Web Threats</h4>
							<p>Your computer and the data stored in it are vulnerable to harm or destruction from malicious (intentionally harmful, hurtful) programs and software that can be found on the Web or sent over email. There are many different types of these harmful programs and software and more are always being created. A common term for them is malware. <strong>Malware</strong> literally means malicious software whose only purpose is to cause harm or destruction to your computer and the data in it.</p>	
							<p>There are many kinds of malware. Common types are: viruses, worms, Trojan horses, spyware and many more.</p>	
							<p>One of the most common types of malware is a <strong>virus</strong>. A virus is created by a human programmer (person who creates and writes programs) who intentionally makes it for damaging and destructive purposes. Another name for these people is hacker. A <strong>hacker</strong> is a computer programmer or expert one who illegally accesses and tampers with computer programs and data.</p>	
							<p>The least serious virus is one that makes more copies of itself, while the most serious virus can erase disks, drives and/or destroy data or even hardware.</p>	
							<p>A virus is usually hidden in an application program that may be transmitted through email or by accessing the Internet. <strong>It is important not to double click on any file (particularly one with a file extension of .exe) transmitted through email unless you are certain of the contents.</strong></p>	
							<p>Many times email address books are used to spread the virus, so even if you know the sender of an email, make certain you check with the sender if you are asked to click on an attachment with a file extension of .exe.</p>	
							<p>Remember that a file with an extension of .exe is a file that begins running when you double click on it. In addition files with a file extension of .zip are compressed (files that have a lot of data are compressed to make them easier to send over the Internet) files and automatically decompress when you double click on them. Be cautious of clicking on them as well.</p>	
							<p>Other malware can open up your computer to remote access by other users, can give access to information about bank accounts, credit cards and other personal data, cause email to be sent from your account, delete files and folders and cause your computer function really slowly and poorly or to stop functioning altogether.</p>	
							<p>You can get these viruses and malware from an email or from a Web site that has been set up for just this purpose. Sometimes Web sites or ads on Web sites are really just covers for viruses and malware.</p>
							<p>If your computer is ever the victim of malware, your computer is considered <strong>infected</strong>. There are programs and software that can remove the malware. But even so, sometimes there is damage to your data that cannot be fixed.</p>
							<p>Can you protect you computer and your data from hackers and malware? Yes, you can; let's learn about that.</p>
						</div>
