							<h4>Protecting Your Computer and Your Data</h4>
							<p>At home and at work, there are good ways to keep your computer safe from malware. One of the most common protections is called a firewall.</p>
							<p>A <strong>firewall</strong> blocks destructive or harmful malware, other programs and hackers from gaining access to your computer or computer network. A firewall can either be a software program or a hardware device.</p>
							<p><strong>Software firewalls</strong> are programs that you install on your computer. They can be set up with "default-deny"ù rules which block all incoming information (email, attachments etc) by default and ask or "prompt"ù you to give permission to allow the information to pass to your computer.</p>
							<p>However, this setup can become time consuming on the user, so instead of "default-deny"ù rules, may programs offer "default-allow" rules. <strong>"Default-allow"</strong> rules allow traffic into the computer or network unless specifically blocked by the user; however, "default-allow"ù setups are also more risky and leave your computer and its data more open to attack. As the user, you choose how much protection to have. The stronger the firewall, the greater the protection, however, it also means less freedom and less openness in regards to Internet and Web access.</p>
							<p>A <strong>hardware firewall</strong> is a router that also acts as a firewall. <strong>Routers</strong> are hardware that is located where two or more networks connect, like where your computer connects to the Internet. Routers forward data where it needs to go. Routers can be set up to act as a firewall as well and many do.</p>
							<p>Routers can provide both wired and wireless connections for the computers connected to them. Wireless routers are not as secure as wired ones. Inexpensive routers can be purchased that allow one or more computers to connect to a single Internet connection. The router connects to the Internet directly and all devices within the home can be connected to the router; therefore the router acts as a safeguard between the Internet and the Local Area Network (LAN). The router obtains the IP address that is exposed to the Internet, not the computer(s) connected to the router.</p>
							<p>However, many <strong>Wi-Fi</strong> (short for <strong>wi</strong>reless <strong>fi</strong>delity and often used to mean a wireless connection) networks are not well secured with passwords and encryption. Someone down the street with a wireless network interface card (NIC) could access the unsecured wi-fi network to connect to the Internet.</p>
							<p>If you are going to connect to any public network such as the Internet, it is important to have anti-virus software running on your computer and to install updates regularly. There are many varieties of good virus protection software available, including free software such as AVG Anti- virus found at <a href="http://www.avg.com">http://www.avg.com</a>. Many of these programs automatically update when you turn on your computer.</p>
